---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Archive Signal"
  description="How the Archive Signal platform keeps podcast hosting static-first, low-cost, and fully versioned."
  pathname="/about/"
>
  <section class="shell page-hero reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">About the platform</p>
    <h1>Static publishing with explicit moving parts.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Archive Signal keeps the stack intentionally simple: JSON content in Git, Astro for page
      generation, Archive.org for media bytes, Netlify for CDN delivery, and hand-built RSS for
      distribution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="shell section about-grid">
    <article class="card reveal">
      <h2>Architecture</h2>
      <p>
        Content lives in `src/content/`. The website is a static Astro build. Feeds and sitemap are
        generated by Node scripts so every deploy reuses the same data model and validation rules.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="card reveal">
      <h2>Publishing workflow</h2>
      <p>
        Episodes are recorded locally, probed with `ffprobe`, uploaded to Archive.org, registered in
        JSON, and then validated before deployment. That keeps the feed deterministic and the diffs
        auditable.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="card reveal">
      <h2>Why this route</h2>
      <p>
        The goal is to avoid recurring media hosting cost without giving up typed content, SEO,
        accessibility, or feed quality. The tradeoff is that the platform is explicit rather than
        magical.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(16rem, 1fr));
    gap: 1.2rem;
  }
</style>
